    # [Scene: Coastal Resilience Lab | Late Night]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Urgent, rhythmic strings—pulsing like a heartbeat; a steady hi-hat drives the momentum]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low hum of servers, distant gulls, the occasional hiss of instruments cycling]
    "You step back into the lab the way you slip into a familiar wound—ache first, then motion. The night here is all-purpose light and blunt instruments; every screen offers the same question: how much do we"
    "owe the harbor, and to whom? Your gloves are damp where you were working the rooftop; your hair has slipped loose from its knot and brushes the base of your neck in restless ticks."
    show elias_rook at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_rook "We under-modeled the compound surges. We didn't account for the way the tide and the storm surge stack—they amplify in ways the scenarios didn't show."
    show ayla_moreno at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ayla_moreno "We thought staged resilience would buy us time. We thought thick strategy could stand in for lived practice. It wasn't enough."

    elias_rook "No. It wasn't. And that's on me—on my team. But it's also on everyone who thought a rendering could be a home."
    "The lab smells faintly of solder and wet concrete; your fingers still taste of peat from the greenhouse. You pull a pressed leaf from your notebook and hold it between thumb and forefinger like an offering."

    elias_rook "Show me."
    "You walk him through the rooftop network—stories of meals split under string lights, of kids running between planters, of a winter where tomatoes fed three families. Your voice tightens and opens, the sort of detail that"
    "slides past policy and lodges in the bones. Elias listens, not as a scientist parsing data but as a person mapping the edges of your life into his models."

    elias_rook "We can integrate reinforced cores. We can anchor the plan with legal covenants that bind future builders. We can instrument prototypes with the stewards—actual neighbors—so the data reflects lived thresholds, not idealized ones."

    ayla_moreno "You want to put sensors where Mateo hangs his nets?"

    elias_rook "And by his shed, and under Kira's rain barrels, and in the hollow where your best basil burned that winter. Everything that matters to you will matter to the model."
    "Your pulse lifts on that small, human specificity. It grounds the abstract until it looks like something you could touch. Around you the lab's sterile hum becomes a kind of promise: engineering married to memory."

    menu:
        "Trace the new reinforcement on the model with Elias":
            "You trace the line with a finger, feeling the cool plastic bump under your nail. Elias watches your movement, then mirrors it, and the plan feels less theoretical and more lived."
        "Sketch the covenant language you want to see":
            "Your handwriting—messy, soil-streaked—lays down phrases: 'community right,' 'restoration fund,' 'steward oversight.' Elias reads them like a litany and nods, as if vows are now technical specs."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue with the following narration."
    "You and Elias trade technical jargon and neighbor-stories until dawn threatens the panes. The cadence between you is no longer defensive; it's collaboration sharpened by apology and action. There are arguments—about budget trade-offs, about the visibility"
    "of certain data—but each disagreement comes with a plan to reconcile it. The lab's clock ticks at a faster tempo: a shared, energized urgency."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Keyboard staccato; the click of models being shifted]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Crescendo—brass cuts in, vivid and clear]

    elias_rook "If we present this—if we stand in front of the council and show the redlines, the trade-offs, and the legally binding protections—it's a risk. But it's the honest one."

    ayla_moreno "We go in with dirt under our nails and a leaf on our chest. No gloss."

    elias_rook "No gloss."
    # [Scene Transition]
    # [Scene: Community Greenhouse | Dawn]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Layered strings soften into a bright, rolling motif; birds call over the distant, restless sea]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Glass condensation pattering, the rustle of leaves]
    "The greenhouse is humid warmth after the lab's cool scrutiny. Steam beads the panes and maps two mornings into one: the night's work and the day's growing. Hands that plant here know a different tempo—slow, stubborn, forgiving. Kira waits among tomato vines, arms crossed but not closed."
    show kira_tseng at center:
        zoom 0.7

    kira_tseng "You did the math. You did the talking. Don't mess this up by sounding like a planner who found religion."

    ayla_moreno "Wouldn't dream of it. I brought dirt and a leaf."
    "You press the pressed leaf between clean palms and tell the stories again—short, luminous anecdotes that ladder up into a full argument. Kira interrupts, as she should, to keep the rhetoric honest."

    kira_tseng "And the legal covenant better say 'no displacement' in language that a judge and a kid on the boardwalk can both point to."

    elias_rook "It will. We're drafting enforceable clauses, community contracting, and a restoration fund. We're proposing a joint oversight council—engineers, residents, and stewards."

    kira_tseng "You involving stewards means more than one seat. That council needs teeth."

    ayla_moreno "It gets seats. It gets teeth. It gets funding. And Mateo—"
    hide elias_rook
    show mateo_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_alvarez "—gets a place at the table or I'll pull out every nail in your model myself."
    "Mateo's laugh is a salt-stiffened bark that fractures the tension. He slaps your shoulder—the world-worn impact like a benediction—and the greenhouse swells with something close to relief. The plants, indifferent and green, seem to lean in, as if the city itself were listening."

    menu:
        "Pin a small map of recovered plots to the greenhouse wall":
            "You tack the map in a crooked line. Neighbors gather, fingers tracing the ink. Someone hums a tune you haven't heard since childhood."
        "Make strong coffee and hand a cup to Mateo":
            "Mateo takes the cup like a treaty. He says, 'This is good work,' and the two words hold like a bridge."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue with the following narration."
    "You and Elias sharpen the presentation the way gardeners prune: remove the dead weight, let the healthy shoots breathe. You rehearse the opening lines until they have the texture of truth. Each rehearsal folds in a"
    "neighbor's anecdote, a clause on enforcement, a technical diagram with a human face. The plan becomes a patchwork quilt—sturdy because every stitch is someone's livelihood."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant city bustle lifting with the morning tide]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Faster tempo, triumphant strings rising]
    # [Scene: Televised Council Meeting | Midday]
    hide ayla_moreno
    hide kira_tseng
    hide mateo_alvarez

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A swelling, decisive chord; percussion underscores the heartbeat of the room]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Murmurs, camera shutters, the bell of council in its ceremonial metallic tone]
    "The chamber is bright and loud, the air electric with a thousand small hopes. Cameras find you as you step to the podium—soil under your nails, the pressed leaf pinned to your jacket like a banner."
    "Someone whispers that your hands look like work. You press the leaf to the podium to let the audience see the grit that has shaped your words."
    show ayla_moreno at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ayla_moreno "This city taught me how to garden and how to grieve. We believed in staged resilience—but we learned we must build with the people who live in the seams. I stand here with soil under my nails because these are not hypothetical places for us. They are kitchens and classrooms and bedtime stories. They are life."
    "Your voice catches the room and then steadies. You tell the stories—short, human vignettes that pull the technical back into the tactile. The cameras hold; the city watches."
    show elias_rook at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_rook "We miscalculated the compound events. That's a hard lesson. Our revised hybrid schematic integrates reinforced cores—engineered defenses that are modular and local—and binds them with legally enforceable community contracts. The pilot we propose will instrument sites with stewards and fund restoration nationally scaled by grant support."
    show jonah_hale at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_hale "We all want safety. My project moves the needle faster. We must choose decisively. Engineering at scale reduces risk immediately."

    ayla_moreno "Decisive doesn't mean unilateral. Fast doesn't mean fair."

    jonah_hale "Ayla, you and I both know the cost of inaction. My concern is getting people out of danger now."

    ayla_moreno "And my concern is getting people out of danger without making them homeless."
    hide ayla_moreno
    show mayor_serena_okoye at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_serena_okoye "We will not choose false binaries in this chamber. We have seen what anger at inaction looks like, and we have seen what unchecked development looks like. I have been up nights balancing the two."
    "The room tightens—every ear tuned to Serena, who carries the weight of votes that will shape neighborhoods. The air tastes of sweat and rain and the metallic tang of cameras. Then, like a struck chord resolving, she speaks with a cadence that feels like decision and mercy folded together."

    mayor_serena_okoye "I call for a pilot program. It will include the hybrid schematic Elias presented, legally binding protections for community gardens, a restoration fund, and oversight by a joint community-engineering council. This pilot will be monitored, funded, and revisited after an agreed period. Kira, we will reserve seats for community stewards."
    hide elias_rook
    show kira_tseng at right:
        zoom 0.7

    kira_tseng "If the seats are real—if they're not a show—then I'll sit."

    mayor_serena_okoye "They will be real."
    "For a breath the chamber seems to dissolve into sound: exhalations, the stamp of notebooks, muted applause swelling like a tide. Jonah's jaw tightens as his carefully arranged plan is reframed, but he does not leave"
    "the room shouting—he argues for amendments, for clarity, for the inclusion of certain commercial zones. His tone shifts from combative to transactional; his posture tells you he will keep pushing, but the scaffolding of compromise is"
    "in place."

    jonah_hale "We will need parameters—clear metrics. We will need to safeguard critical infrastructure."
    hide jonah_hale
    show ayla_moreno at center:
        zoom 0.7

    ayla_moreno "And we will need binding clauses that prevent displacement. We will need restoration money that goes to the people who lost plots, not just the projects."
    "Mayor Serena nods, taking notes with the weary precision of someone who has carried a city through storms. The council votes in favor of a pilot—not an all-or-nothing triumph but a binding step toward protecting what the harbor holds: its people and their gardens."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The bell of council, a solid strike; a collective, fragile cheer]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Full, exultant strings; a brass lift that feels like sunlight breaking a stormcloud]
    hide mayor_serena_okoye
    show mateo_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_alvarez "You kept your hands dirty. That's how you win my trust.' (he slaps your shoulder, louder this time, and his fingers leave a dark crescent on your coat) 'We may have lost a corner, chica. But we have a treaty now."

    ayla_moreno "We did better than bargain—we made a promise."
    "Outside, neighbors spill into the boardwalk with tired grins and damp eyes. Kira stands beside you, bruised but steady, squeezing your hand in a small, fierce clasp. Elias arrives with his tablet tucked under his arm;"
    "he doesn't say anything for a long, perfect second—he simply squeezes your gloved hand and his fingers find yours like a practiced knot."
    hide kira_tseng
    show elias_rook at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_rook "We built something together. Imperfect, but together."

    ayla_moreno "That is enough to start."
    "The city's air tastes like salt and coffee and sudden, brittle laughter. The pilot is not victory over fate; it is a commitment to fight with shared tools. Some plots will take years to recover. Some"
    "losses are permanent. But the program—funded, legally anchored, and monitored with community stewards—creates a scaffolding where the harbor's people can repair and replant rather than flee."
    hide ayla_moreno
    hide mateo_alvarez
    hide elias_rook

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rising chorus—warm, resolute]
    "You move through the montage like a gardener among survivors, cheeks raw from wind and smiling anyway. Each reclaimed bed is a small flag of defiance. Each clause in the covenant is a stitch that keeps"
    "the fabric whole. The city, imperfect and stubborn, learns to hold both steel and soil."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Laughter, the clink of a ceremonial shovel, a child's high exclamation]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sustained, hopeful brass and strings; percussive beat slows into a steady march]
    show elias_rook at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_rook "You were fierce today. You made them listen."
    show ayla_moreno at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ayla_moreno "You did too. You made them afraid of losing the math, then showed them how the math could protect the things that aren't numbers."

    elias_rook "So—will you let me keep fixing things with you?"

    ayla_moreno "If fixing things involves your stubborn models and my stubborn hands—yes."
    "His hand finds yours and squeezes—a small, steady band of contact that says more than any promise. The intimacy between you feels earned, tempered in late-night lab lights and the greenhouse's humid air. Around you, people"
    "continue to work, to argue, to celebrate; hope here is sweaty and busy and unmistakable."
    show mateo_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_alvarez "Come on, lovers. If you two stop making out, there's a plot that needs turning!"

    ayla_moreno "We're on it!"
    "You laugh; Elias laughs; the greenhouse responds with a chorus of human noise. The pilot will need refinement. Jonah will continue to push for modifications. There will be storms and tests and votes yet to come."
    "But the covenant is inked; the council has a new mechanism for oversight; funds have been earmarked for restoration. The harbor will not be the same—and it will not be lost to a single vision imposed"
    "from above."
    hide elias_rook
    hide ayla_moreno
    hide mateo_alvarez

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A final, swelling chord that resolves into a gentle, ongoing loop—work continuing]
    "You walk the boardwalk that evening with Elias at your side, hands still linked. The city smells of seaweed and grilled food from a nearby stall, of soil and the acetone tang of freshly printed legal pages. Your heart is not unburdened—work remains—but it beats with a clear, steady hope."
    "You feel Mateo's older hand on your shoulder like a benediction; Kira's presence is a constant nudge toward accountability; Mayor Serena's decision is the city's reluctant, courageous pulse toward compromise. Elias's squeeze is the quiet promise between you: to keep arguing, to keep designing, to keep planting."
    "The pilot is a beginning that demands vigilance, skill, and stubborn love. You have rooted something that did not have to be ruin—soil and clause intertwined. That mix of grit and law, of compost and covenant,"
    "is the city's new scaffolding. You have won no fairy-tale ending; you have, instead, a working plan and a hand to hold as you build it."

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet, resolved piano; a single sustaining string holds the last note]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_6 at full_bg
    "THE END"
